{
  "text": "Scientific RepoRts | 7: 4364 | DOI:10.1038/s41598-017-04231-5 supporting a mechanistic cooperation between various signaling pathways for the control of inflammatory responses. We also tested the therapeutic effects of the P2X7R blockade on the survival of septic mice. No significant differences were found in mice receiving antagonists compared with the control animals in our study. However, the study by Csoka et al. [CITATION_1] showed that the survival rates of P2X7 knockout mice were significantly lower than CLP mice, indicating that the ATP interaction with P2X7R is protective. This discrepancy may be attributed to the inhibited inflammatory responses and mitigated intestinal epithelial barrier injuries upon the administration of antagonists in septic mice.",
  "correct_citation": {
